│ process. This is unexpected because the current SCC should   │
│ remain valid throughout the pass execution.\n\n### 2.        │
│ Analyzing `opt`'s Log\nThe log shows that the `coro-split`   │
│ pass modifies the call graph by switching an internal        │
│ reference edge to a call edge. This transformation likely    │
│ causes the invalidation of the SCC containing `foo` (the     │
│ coroutine being processed).\n\n### 3. Root Cause             │
│ Analysis\nFrom the debugger evaluation:\n- The `InitialC`    │
│ SCC (the SCC being processed) is the same as `C`.\n-         │
│ `InitialC` is present in `UR.InvalidatedSCCs`, meaning it    │
│ was invalidated during the transformation.\n- The `RefSCC`   │
│ pointer (`RC`) is null, which suggests that the outer        │
│ `RefSCC` of the invalidated SCC is no longer valid.\n\nThe   │
│ invalidation likely occurs because the transformation        │
│ modifies the call graph in a way that splits or merges SCCs, │
│ and the analysis manager is not updated correctly to reflect │
│ these changes. Specifically, the `CWorklist` and             │
│ `InvalidatedSCCs` structures are not synchronized, leading   │
│ to the assertion failure.\n\n### 4. Proposed Edit            │
│ Point(s)\nTo fix this issue, we need to ensure that the      │
│ `CWorklist` and `InvalidatedSCCs` structures are updated     │
│ consistently when the call graph is modified. This can be    │
│ achieved by adding a check before enqueuing the SCC back     │
│ onto the worklist:\n\n```cpp\n1154       if                  │
│ (!UR.InvalidatedSCCs.count(C))\n```\n\nThis ensures that     │
│ only valid SCCs are added to the worklist, preventing the    │
│ assertion failure.\n\n### 5. Conclusion\nThe proposed fix    │
│ prevents invalid SCCs from being processed further, ensuring │
│ the consistency of the analysis manager and avoiding the     │
│ assertion failure. This change is localized and should not   │
│ affect other parts of the codebase."})                       │
